    {
      "id": "/page/0/TextInlineMath/2",
      "block_type": "TextInlineMath",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"TextInlineMath\">A key assumption of Duffie-Singleton is the modeling of recovery in the event of default as an exogenously given fraction of the market value of the defaultable claim immediately prior to default. Under this assumption, the possibility of default on a claim can be priced by default-adjusting the interest rate with which the future cash flow (or payoff) from the claim is discounted. That is to say that today's <math display=\"inline\">(t = 0)</math>value <math display=\"inline\">V_0</math> of a claim with the (possibly random) payoff X at time <math display=\"inline\">t = T</math> can be calculated as the expectation under the spot risk-neutral measure <math display=\"inline\">O</math>,</p>",
      "page": 235,
      "polygon": [
        [
